   <h1>Re: [T2] Jump start blues!</h1>
   <b>"cmeanley" <cmeanley(-at-)pacificcoast.net></b><br/>
   <i>2001-10-09 04:18:26+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>Er, never say never, last westy I bought had a red ground wire, went to
charge the battery and had to look twice. My mind said red=positive, my
subconcious asked why it was on the wrong side of the battery. Lesson here,
always question what the po might have done.
Chuck
72 westy
77 riviera
----- Original Message -----
From: "Mike Soultanian" 
To: "ovalwindow" 
Cc: 
Sent: Monday, October 08, 2001 8:43 PM
Subject: Re: [T2] Jump start blues!


> RED DOESN'T GO TO NEGATIVE, RED GOES TO PLUS!!!!!!!  Beat that in your
> head over and over and over!  And then one more time!
>
> I think it's probably safe to say that red is always positive, except in
> some special wiring situations, but more often than not, it is positive!
>
> Don't hook it up the other way unless you want to FRY everything.  If
> you have any radio's or other devices, those are prone to FRY too!!  My
> friend fried his amp by hooking it up backwards.. that was a costly
> mistake.
>
> The negative terminal should be hooked up to the ground wire.  That is
> the wire that goes straight to the chassis.
>
> And when you hook up an extra jumper battery, you hook + to + and - to
> -, not the other way.  By doing this, you put the batteries and parallel
> and increase the amps available to the starter.
>
> I'd first hook your battery up the correct way.  Hook up the wiring
> harness with all the red cables on it (and a big fat (probably black)
> one that goes to the starter) to the positive(+) terminal and the other
> braided one that goes to the chassis to negative (-).
>
> put in the new one, and test out the voltage at different points in the
> car.  Fuse box is probably a good place.  You should have 12v on your
> meter.  This is with the key off.
>
> Then try and see if the car will start.  If it does, go and test the
> voltage again and it should be running at around 13.7 volts.  If it is,
> your voltage regulator is still working correctly.  If it's higher, then
> it's not working.  I don't know the reprocussions of having a bad
> regulator so be careful..
>
> I don't how else you'd check your regulator, but I'm sure if I missed
> something that someone else will chime in.
>
> good luck!
> Mike
>
>
>
> ovalwindow wrote:
> >
> > Hello,
> >
> > Lurker named Milo here.  I've got a problem in my '69
> > Westy that
> > I probably shouldn't have, but nonetheless - I do...
> >
> > I left it at a friend's house for a few weeks, came
> > back, and the
> > battery was dead.  Simple enough I thought - I hooked
> > jumpers up
> > to it from my car and it started right up.  But as
> > soon as I unhooked
> > the jumpers, it died.  This is stange I thought!  So
> > off I run to the
> > store, fork over some bread for a new battery, and
> > think - I hate
> > buying a new battery but this is simple enough, quit
> > complaining...
> > Little was I to know!
> >
> > I get back, and notice that the red cable in the back
> > of my bus is
> > indeed, hooked up to the negative terminal, and that
> > when I jump
> > started it, I had the + from the car hooked up the -
> > of the bus, and
> > vise-versa....  Well, that explains why she wouldn't
> > stay running.
> > And man, was that battery hot when I took it out of
> > the bus!
> >
> > After second guessing myself a few times, I conclude
> > beyond a reasonable
> > doubt that yes - the red should go to the negative
> > terminal, etc.  Man,
> > was that hard to do though!  Something about hooking
> > red up to negative
> > that really goes against the grain ya know.
> >
> > My problem is this.  My red light is now on, and I
> > seem to recall
> > somewhere that what I've just done is reversed the
> > "charge" in the
> > generator - not sure if that was Muir, Usenet, the
> > list, etc.  But
> > I seem to recall reading this.  The archives couldn't
> > bear this out
> > however.  Hell, maybe I dreamed it sometime, but it's
> > my hunch.
> >
> > Anyone have any suggestions from previous experience?
> > Did I fry my
> > Voltage Regulator, ruin my generator, or just put a
> > magnetic hex
> > on the gennie that could be removed by a shop w/ the
> > right type
> > of magnet.  Any and all suggestions would be greatly
> > appreciated!
> >
> > Geez, if I'd have just shut the key all the way off
> > before taking
> > off that one night none of this would have
> > happened.... *sighs*
> >
> > THANKS!  Milo
